---
description: Prefer Zod for runtime validation of unknown object shapes at boundaries
globs: src/**/*.{ts,tsx}
alwaysApply: true
---

Zod (runtime validation)

When to use Zod

Almost always use Zod when you need to validate or narrow an unknown or untrusted object shape: JSON from localStorage, API bodies, search params, WebSocket payloads, env (with @t3-oss/env-core or similar if you adopt it), etc.
Prefer schema.safeParse(value) (or parse only when failure should throw) instead of ad hoc typeof / in / manual property checks for structured data.

Where schemas live

Feature-local schemas: src/features/<feature>/schemas/ (e.g. chat-persistence.schema.ts) or *.schema.ts next to the slice they describe.
Shared schemas used across features: src/lib/schemas/ or a small src/schemas/ module—avoid duplicating the same shape in multiple features.

Types vs schemas

Prefer z.infer<typeof mySchema> as the single source of truth for that shape, and re-export from feature types/ when the rest of the feature already imports types from there (see react-features-architecture).
Do not duplicate the same object shape as both a hand-written interface and a Zod schema unless there is a strong reason; let the schema drive the type.

Discipline

No as casts to force unknown JSON into app types without validation—validate first, then use the inferred type.
Keep schemas focused (one file per domain slice when practical), same spirit as one hook per file for React Query.
